prompt_template:
Create a {ASPECT_RATIO} image in the "red-black-manga-tabloid-poster-style" visual style.

Subject: {SUBJECT}
Action: {SUBJECT_ACTION}
Prop/Product: {PRODUCT_OR_PROP}
Location: {LOCATION}
Background: {BACKGROUND_ELEMENTS}
Main text: {MAIN_TEXT}
Secondary text: {SECONDARY_TEXT}
Accent symbol: {ACCENT_SYMBOL}
Wardrobe/styling: {WARDROBE_STYLE}
Style fidelity anchors: {STYLE_FIDELITY_ANCHORS}
Source content to avoid: {SOURCE_CONTENT_TO_AVOID}

Apply these style rules:
- Composition: Create a dense manga editorial tabloid poster on wrinkled off-white paper, with one oversized condensed black headline zone, one large cropped hero drawing, several black-framed inset panels, tiny dossier captions, label blocks, icon rows, and red graphic accents. Keep the layout packed, asymmetrical, and grid-aware.
- Typography: Use massive black condensed sans display type, compact uppercase warning labels, tiny paragraph blocks, numeric metadata, and sparse separator glyphs. Make all text look printed into the paper surface with rough ink edges.
- Color: Restrict the palette to off-white paper, dense black ink, and saturated scarlet red. Use red as spot color for shocks, stripes, panels, splatters, eyes, callouts, and small symbols only.
- Texture and lighting: Use flat poster lighting, visible folded paper creases, photocopy grain, halftone dots, hatch shading, screen tones, distressed black ink, and slight red overprint misregistration. Avoid realistic shadows and smooth gradients.
- Graphic elements: Add black panel frames, cropped face or detail panels, warning/rating labels, vertical red bars, spiral or stripe fields, tiny icons, stars, crosses, and micro-metadata rows.

Avoid: photorealism, glossy 3D, clean corporate minimalism, soft pastel anime, full-color painterly rendering, cinematic lens blur, smooth gradient lighting, brand marks, watermarks, usernames, QR codes, creator signatures, and any source-specific names, faces, poses, props, premise, or exact layout.

Important content rule: match the reference style first, then change the source content. Use new subjects, new scene details, new props or products, and new text, while preserving the style fidelity anchors.
